docs:
Lexeme is the most basic unit of the 𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑦 lexicon and represents a single placeholder value in an arithmetic matrix.

NOTE: All bases from Base2 to Base256 are well-defined in the lexicon, but the most common are aliased for convenience.
related: See Lexeme, Digit, Binary, Ternary, Octal, Decimal, Hexadecimal, and Sexagesimal

types.name: Digit
types.docs: Digits are a single placeholder - if you wish to describe any abstract digit, use this interface.

types.name: Base2
types.docs:
Base2 represents a single binary placeholder Digit - see Base2Digits

NOTE: All 洧노洧녰洧녵洧녽 placeholder lexeme digits are hexadecimal.
